    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-04-25T16:46:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-04-25T16:46:00-05:00" n="225"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d225">
                <head>225. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Saudi Arabia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d225fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 641.86a/4–2356. Secret; Priority. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_NDD1">Newsom</persName> and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName>. Repeated <gloss
                            target="#t_Niact1">niact</gloss> to London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-04-25T16:46:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1956—4:46 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>553. Jidda’s 480.<note n="2" xml:id="d225fn2">Telegram 480, April 23, confirmed
                        Saudi acceptance of the <persName corresp="#p_PRB1">Dodds–Parker</persName>
                        mission. The Embassy also reported that the King would accept Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_PRW1">Parkes</persName>’ credentials before the
                        start of the discussions. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>)</note> Embassy
                    requested bring following attention <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> in
                    manner you deem most effective perhaps through Azzam:</p>
                <p>US welcomes decision <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> begin discussion current differences. Decision
                    represents act high statesmanship both on part King and present <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> Government. <gloss target="#t_UKG1">UKG</gloss>
                    however fears recently reported actions on part <gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                        >SAG</gloss> which appear directed against British on eve of talks may give
                    unfortunate impression in <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> and create
                    atmosphere not conducive fruitful results. <gloss target="#t_UKG1">UKG</gloss>
                    has special reference to anti–British interpretations placed by Radio Cairo on
                    Yemeni–Saudi–Egyptian treaty and on <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> loan to
                    Yemen. Earlier <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> had expressed concern re
                    reported expulsion locust mission, arms distribution on Aden border. <gloss
                        target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> discussed two latter actions with Azzam April
                    16.</p>
                <p>US has also received indirectly reports Saudi troop movements southward toward
                    Buraimi (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 479<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d225fn3">Telegram 479, April 23, conveyed an unconfirmed report of a
                        Saudi airlift of soldiers from Riyadh and Dhahran to “Shira, ‘near
                        Buraimi’.” (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi> 780.022/4–2356)</note>). In event
                    these reports substantiated and become known in <gloss target="#t_UK1"
                        >UK</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> anticipates further British
                    hesitation to begin or continue talks. While US appreciates such movement may be
                    normal defensive maneuver and may have begun before recent agreement on talks,
                    any <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> assurances regarding these movements
                    which can be passed on to <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> might be
                    helpful.</p>
                <p>US continuing stress to <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> (see following telegram
                    to London<note n="4" xml:id="d225fn4">Not printed. (<hi rend="italic"
                        >Ibid.</hi>)</note>) only real solution these various problems lies in
                    immediate opening talks.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
